{"id":"backslide","term":"Backslide","source":"Easton's Bible Dictionary (M.G. Easton, 1897)","html":"<p>To draw back or apostatize in matters of religion (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Acts 21:21\">Acts 21:21</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"2 Thessalonians 2:3\">2 Thess. 2:3</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"1 Timothy 4:1\">1 Tim. 4:1</a>). This may be either partial (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Proverbs 14:14\">Prov. 14:14</a>) or complete (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Hebrews 6:4\">Heb. 6:4-6</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Hebrews 10:38\">10:38</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Hebrews 10:39\">39</a>). The apostasy may be both doctrinal and moral.</p>\n\u0000","refs":["Acts 21:21","2 Thessalonians 2:3","1 Timothy 4:1","Proverbs 14:14","Hebrews 6:4","Hebrews 10:38","Hebrews 10:39"]}